                    "company": "University of Groningen",
                    "description": "This job entails five year research (60%) and teaching duties (40%). A short description of my project:\n\nRetracing Digital Memory Practices\nMedia have historically played a pivotal role in the construction of memory. On the personal level, people have used, for example, scrap books and diaries to capture memory of events close to them. On a societal level, institutional media such as newspapers and traditions like memorial days contribute to and shape collective forms of memory. On both levels, new practices and forms of memory have emerged throughout history, ranging from cave painting(s) in prehistory to the \u2018live broadcasting of history\u2019 on television. My PhD project examines emerging memory practices in what can be called the \u2018digital age\u2019.\n\nDigital memory practices blur the line between the private and the public spheres of memory. Moreover, other dichotomies, such as \u2018the amateur and the professional\u2019, are problematized in an age in which people have access to the tools for \u2018mass self-communication\u2019 and, potentially, reach global audiences. For example, one case study in my project focuses on the ways in which private and media memories entangle on memorial Facebook pages. Another zooms in on the practice of \u2018video witnessing\u2019 and how this reconfigures memory of conflicts and atrocity. A third case study delves into the wealth of remixes that are made from iconic news photographs. With these case studies, I hope to retrace how existing and emerging media practices construct memory in contemporary mediatized society and culture.\n\nThis project is supervised by Prof. Dr. Marcel Broersma and Dr. Ansgard Heinrich and is sponsored by the Groningen Research Institute for the Study of Culture (ICOG).",
